# Coding style

## Package manager

When working in TypeScript or JavaScript, use **yarn** as the package manager. Use yarn when running tests, scripts, or executing `node_modules` binaries. Do not use npx or npm.

## No IIFEs for local values

Do **not** wrap logic in an immediately invoked function expression just to assign a local `const`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const dateRange = (() => {
  if (!selection) return {mode: 'dynamic', range: 'PAST_30_DAYS'};
  if (selection.preset === 'custom') return {mode: 'fixed', start, end};
  return {mode: 'dynamic', range: MAP[selection.preset]};
})();

// ✅ GOOD — plain control flow in the same scope
let dateRange: CreateComplianceAuditTemplateInput['dateRange'];
if (!selection) {
  dateRange = {mode: 'dynamic', range: 'PAST_30_DAYS'};
} else if (selection.preset === 'custom') {
  dateRange = {mode: 'fixed', start, end};
} else {
  dateRange = {mode: 'dynamic', range: MAP[selection.preset]};
}
```

### Allowed

- `useMemo(() => ..., [deps])`, `useCallback`, `useEffect` — React/hook callbacks are not IIFEs for this rule
- IIFEs in tests or build scripts when there is a concrete reason (module scope, legacy constraint)

### When logic is reused

Extract a **named function** at module scope if it is shared. Do not use an anonymous IIFE at the call site.

## No single-use local variables

Do **not** declare a local variable that is referenced in only one place. Inline the expression at the use site.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — binding used once
const isQueryEnabled = enabled && Boolean(queryParams.locationIds?.length);

useQuery({
  enabled: isQueryEnabled,
});

// ✅ GOOD — inline
useQuery({
  enabled: enabled && Boolean(queryParams.locationIds?.length),
});
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const label = item.name.trim();
return <span>{label}</span>;

// ✅ GOOD
return <span>{item.name.trim()}</span>;
```

### Allowed

- Locals used **two or more times** (avoid repeating the same expression)
- Locals that exist only to give a **non-obvious** value a name where inlining would hurt readability (rare — prefer a named function if the expression is complex)
- Destructured bindings and parameters (not “declared then used once” temps)
- Hook return values kept for a stable dependency array when the same value is listed in deps
